INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd46894bc-f6be-43af-815e-fe1eafd242cf',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$gRPC vs tRPC — End-to-End Type Safety Without .proto Files$escape$,
  $escape$For gRPC developers, tRPC feels structurally familiar but trades protobuf schemas for TypeScript's type system. Instead of `.proto` contracts and codegen, tRPC infers types directly from your router — zero schema drift because server and client share the same TypeScript source.

tRPC mirrors gRPC's call taxonomy: `query` (unary read), `mutation` (unary write), and `subscription` (server streaming via WebSockets). The `AppRouter` type is your contract — exported and imported directly, no generated stubs.

The React Query integration is first-class: `trpc.user.getById.useQuery({ id })` wraps `useQuery` with full inference — no separate type declarations, no `grpc-web` proxy layer, no manual cache invalidation boilerplate.

The tradeoffs vs gRPC are real: tRPC is TypeScript-only and HTTP/1.1-based. You lose HTTP/2 multiplexing, binary framing, and polyglot support. Streaming is WebSocket-backed, not true bidirectional gRPC streaming.

Choose tRPC for full-stack TypeScript monorepos where compile-time safety outweighs protocol performance. Keep gRPC where you need cross-language clients, high-throughput binary transport, or true bidirectional streaming.$escape$,
  $escape$// server: router replaces .proto + codegen
const appRouter = router({
  user: router({
    getById: publicProcedure
      .input(z.object({ id: z.string() }))
      .query(({ input }) => db.user.findUnique({ where: { id: input.id } })),
  }),
});

export type AppRouter = typeof appRouter; // the contract

// client: inferred — no generated stubs
const user = await trpc.user.getById.query({ id: "abc" });

// React Query hook — replaces grpc-web + useEffect pattern
const { data, isLoading } = trpc.user.getById.useQuery({ id: "abc" });$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
